# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# Impact Analyzer — Environment Configuration
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# Copy this file to .env and fill in your values before starting the backend.

# ── Server ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
CORS_ORIGIN=http://localhost:5173

# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# AMAZON BEDROCK — AI-enhanced impact reports + scenario-based Q&A
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# SETUP (3 steps)
# ───────────────
# Step 1 — Create an IAM user in AWS Console with this inline policy:
#
#   {
#     "Version": "2012-10-17",
#     "Statement": [{
#       "Effect": "Allow",
#       "Action": ["bedrock:InvokeModel"],
#       "Resource": "*"
#     }]
#   }
#
#   Generate an Access Key for that user and paste it below.
#
# Step 2 — Enable your chosen model in the AWS Console:
#   AWS Console → Amazon Bedrock → Model access → Request access
#
# Step 3 — Fill in the four variables below, then restart the backend.
#   The service activates automatically — no other code changes needed.
#
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID=your_aws_access_key_here
AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=your_aws_secret_key_here
AWS_REGION=us-east-1

# ── Model selection ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Must match a model you have enabled in Bedrock Model Access (Step 2).
#
# Option A — Anthropic Claude 3.5 Sonnet (best quality, recommended):
BEDROCK_MODEL_ID=anthropic.claude-3-5-sonnet-20241022-v2:0
#
# Option B — Amazon Nova Pro (AWS-native, lower cost):
# BEDROCK_MODEL_ID=amazon.nova-pro-v1:0
#
# Option C — Anthropic Claude 3 Haiku (fastest and cheapest):
# BEDROCK_MODEL_ID=anthropic.claude-3-haiku-20240307-v1:0
